Edward Ramon, <br><br>
You talk about people fearing war. Isn't it true that<br>
most people fear war and the possibility of facing death.<br>
From that basic animal instinct, comes caution and a<br>
hightened awareness that helps keep one alive.<br><br>
Yes I fear war, but that was not why I did not go. My<br>
political views were developed from work I did in the<br>
civil rights movement, long before I was conscious of<br>
the war and its imact on my life. <br><br>
.......................................<br><br>
As for the anti-war movement... People joined the movement<br>
for many reasons.Some were politically motivated, some<br>
people did it for perosnal ego reasons and some because<br>
they were afraid of dying. I find that judging ones motives<br>
is hard to do. It is easier and better to judge ones actions.<br><br>
As for communism. Yes there was a part of the movement <br>
that was communists. Communism has a tradition in the US<br>
that is a valid ideology, whether we like it or not. Again<br>
judge what people do, not what they think. Like most people<br>
communists did good things and bad things. They are people<br>
and not monsters, and yes they did believe that the war was<br>
wrong.<br><br>
As for the anti-war movemnent being involved in drugs,<br>
sex and violence. I think that those who went to Nam <br>
also had plenty of opportunity to be involved in violence,<br>
drugs and sex. <br><br>
I would like to hear about the following from the <br>
non-anti-war prospective.<br><br>
Why were we in Vietnam? What gave us the right to <br>
be there? Could we have accomplished our objectives <br>
without going to war, and for that matter what was<br>
our real objectives.<br><br>
There is a great deal of anger against the anti-war<br>
protester. From my perspective it seems as though thtere <br>
should be a great deal of anger against the US govt.who<br>
sent you there. Why don't I see this in the posts?<br><br>
Thanks for your replys.
